    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's an interesting distinction. You mentioned Case B's circumstances might lead to a \"more severe penalty\" because of his background. Can you expand on that? Specifically, how does a judge weigh the \"unstable life\" and \"underserved neighborhood\" as aggravating factors versus mitigating factors? For example, could those same socioeconomic struggles be argued as a reason for leniency instead of harsher scrutiny?",
